This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
9:48 AM - Case not called on the Record
Attorney Alissa Schaller in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Attorney Mindy M. Nolan appeared by video for Tracy L Valentine.  
Defendant Tracy L Valentine appeared by video.
Attorney Nolan requests another hearing date.  Court grants.
Hearing scheduled for December 2, 2022 at 09:00 am.

Cash bail previously posted to be refunded to poster. Defendant is not to have any violent contact with victim A/witnesses A & B listed in the Criminal Complaint/Victim Identification Key.   Defendant is not to share, reproduce or distribute any personal and/or identifying information about the crime victim(s), except to their attorney. Absolute sobriety, defendant is not to possess or consume any alcohol. Defendant is not to use/possess any controlled substances without a valid prescription and take as prescribed. Defendant not to possess any drug paraphernalia.

8:19 AM District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Niki Kane. Defendant Tracy L Valentine in court.  Attorney Mindy M. Nolan in court for Tracy L Valentine.  Victim A appeared in court.

Defense acknowledges receipt of complaint and waives reading of complaint. 
Service admitted/advised of charges and potential penalties. 
Attorney Nolan raises a probable cause as it relates to Count 1 and presents arguments and requests to dismiss Count 1.
Ms. Kane presents counter arguments and states probable cause is found in the four (4) corners of the criminal complaint and requests to deny the Defense's oral motion.
The Court places its findings on the record.
The Court finds probable cause as it relates to Count 1 and denies the Defense's oral Motion to Dismiss Count 1.
Victim A presents a statement.
NOT GUILTY PLEA ENTERED.
Hearing scheduled for October 14, 2022 at 09:30 am.
